---

## Q1. Derivation from Eq. (4) to Eq. (5); the appearance of $\hat{\theta}$

The reviewer is right that $\hat{\theta}$ enters Eq. (5) without introduction.
This is an omission on our part rather than a substantive step.

Equations (3)--(5) describe the two stages of the empirical Bayes procedure.
Stage 1 (Eq. 3) estimates the prior parameters by maximum marginal likelihood,
producing $\hat{\theta}$. Stage 2 then computes the posterior *conditional on
that estimate*, i.e. treating $\hat\theta$ as fixed:

$$
p_{\mathrm{post}}(\beta) \;=\; p(\beta \mid y, X, D, \hat\theta, \sigma^2)
\;\propto\; p(y \mid X, \beta, \sigma^2)\, g(\beta; D, \hat\theta).
$$

The proportionality in Eq. (5) is with respect to $\beta$, with the marginal
likelihood absorbed into the normalising constant.

\rev{Revision: we now define $\hat\theta$ explicitly at Eq. (3), carry it
through the conditioning bar in Eq. (4), and add one sentence noting that this
plug-in step is the standard EB approximation --- the posterior does not account
for uncertainty in $\hat\theta$.}

